                                                                                                                                                   Pak to adopt tougher approach
    Karachi: The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) is planning a more straight-forward approach to revive the shifting the 2011 World Cup matches out of the country at the annual International Cricket Council (ICC) meeting in June.
    The media reports said that the PCB has decided to adopt a tougher approach as Pakistan still remains upset with the World Cup matches moved out of the country without their consent although ICC chief executive Haroon Lorgat had claimed it a unanimous.
    ldquo;The chairman will also take up the issue of Pakistan rsquo;s hosting rights and fees at the coming meeting, rdquo; the report said. Interestingly the Pakistan rsquo;s cricket community has welcomed the strong statement of former ICC president Ehsan Mani in which he directly blamed India for having the World Cup matches moved out of Pakistan.
    PCB plan
    Karachi: The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) has directed all its top players to make themselves available for the national Twenty20 championship to be held in Lahore from May 26 to 29 as preparation for the ensuing ICC World Twenty20 in England. ldquo;The tournament will be held over a four-day period as the team has to leave for England on the 30th. We have asked all the top players to ensure they play in the tournament, rdquo; PCB chief operating officer Saleem Altaf said.
    CA spin summit
    Melbourne: Cricket Australia (CA) has called for a ldquo;spin summit rdquo; at the Centre of Excellence (COE) in Brisbane later this year in order to find a suitable for Shane Warne, who retired from international cricket in 2007. Warne rsquo;s mentor Terry Jenner and Centre of Excellence spin bowling coach John Davison, will try to find an answer as to why Australia rsquo;s spinners are struggling to make an impact at all levels of the game. Spin experts felt the problem lies partly with bowlers lacking perseverance and also with captains not knowing how to use them.
    Bermuda coach
    Hamilton: Bermuda rsquo;s national cricket team coach Gus Logie will step down in September when his contract expires. The Bermuda Cricket Board made the announcement Wednesday, after some players called for Logie rsquo;s dismissal following Bermuda rsquo;s poor performance last month at the ICC World Cup Qualifiers in South Africa.The team missed a World Cup slot by finishing ninth, lost its one-day International status and was relegated to Division Two of the ICC Trophy.
